  "22": {
    "John Trapp": "Upon all ] So that none shall hinder their happiness.\nVer.\n22. Upon all] So that none shall hinder their happiness.\nVer.",
    "Charles H. Talbert": "Two points comprise the argument. First,\nAbraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]` was found faithful when tested. This is a reference to the sacrifice of Isaac in Gen\n22. Second, as a result, it was\nreckoned to him as righteousness. This is a reference to Gen\n22. Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]`\u2019s two points are clear-cut. First, according to Gen 15,\nwhich comes before ch. 17, Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]` is justified through faith. Second, ch. 15, which speaks about his justification, comes\nbefore ch. 17, which talks about Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]`\u2019s circumcision. He was, therefore, justified through faith before he was ever\ncircumcised. This shows Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]` was the father of Gentiles `[group_Gentiles_Ref]` who have faith just as much as of Jews who have faith.\nIn these three sources one can see how basically the same material can be used by different authors in a variety of ways.\nAbraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]`\u2019s being reckoned righteous in connection with his faith\nwas, moreover, while he was as yet uncircumcised (= a Gentile).\n[v_Psa_32_1] Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]` asked, for whom is the blessing mentioned in\nonly for Jews? Or is it also for Gentiles ("
  },
