  "28": {
    "John Trapp": "A man is justified by faith ] Here St Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]` shows himself a pure Lutheran, and is therefore sharply and blasphemously censured by some Jesuits for a hot-headed person, who was so transported with the pangs of zeal and eagerness beyond all compass in most of his disputes, that there was no great reckoning to be made of his assertions. (Speculum Europae.) Yea, he was dangerous to read, as savouring of heresy in some places, and better perhaps he had never written. Four years before the Council of Trent, Cardinal Contarenus asserted the doctrine of justification by faith alone, in a just treatise, and was therefore soon after poisoned. Cardinal Pole is thought to have been sound in this point. Bellarmine reproves Pighius for consenting to Luther herein, whom he undertook to confute, and yet Bellarmine himself with his tutissimum est, it is most safe. doth as much upon the matter. Magna est veritas, et valebit, Great is the truth, and shall prevail.\nVer.\n28. A man is justified by faith] Here St Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]` shows himself a pure Lutheran, and is therefore sharply and blasphemously censured by some Jesuits for a hot-headed person, who was so transported with the pangs of zeal and eagerness beyond all compass in most of his disputes, that there was no great reckoning to be made of his assertions. (Speculum Europae.) Yea, he was dangerous to read, as savouring of heresy in some places, and better perhaps he had never written. Four years before the Council of Trent, Cardinal Contarenus asserted the doctrine of justification by faith alone, in a just treatise, and was therefore soon after poisoned. Cardinal Pole is thought to have been sound in this point. Bellarmine reproves Pighius for consenting to Luther herein, whom he undertook to confute, and yet Bellarmine himself with his tutissimum est, it is most safe. doth as much upon the matter. Magna est veritas, et valebit, Great is the truth, and shall prevail.\nVer.",
    "Commentary Vol. 163": "), and it is further confirmed, that Jews and Gentiles `[group_Gentiles_Ref]`, with respect to\ntheir state and condition God-ward, are on a level; he is the God of the\n[v_Rom_3_29] one, as well as of the other, (<450329>Romans 3:29), and this appears by his\njustifying both in one and the same way, through faith in the righteousness\n53\n[v_Rom_3_30] of this Son, (<450330>Romans 3:30), and the chapter is concluded by obviating\nan objection that might be made, that through this doctrine of justification\n[v_Rom_3_31] by faith the law is made void, and is of no use, (<450331>Romans 3:31), to which\nthe apostle answers, that this is so far from being fact, that the law is\nestablished by it.\nVer"
  },
  "29": {
    "John Trapp": "Is he the God of the Jews only ] That is, Doth he justify the Jews only? For he is their God only whom he justifieth. Now men are said to be justified effectively by God, apprehensively by faith, declaratively by good works. The schoolmen are very unsound in this capital article of justification, and are therefore the less to be regarded. Nam quae de gratia Dei iustificante scholastici seribunt, commentitia universa existimo, saith Cardinal Pighius, who is therefore much condemned by Bellarmine, but without cause.\nVer.\n29. Is he the God of the Jews only] That is, Doth he justify the Jews only? For he is their God only whom he justifieth. Now men are said to be justified effectively by God, apprehensively by faith, declaratively by good works. The schoolmen are very unsound in this capital article of justification, and are therefore the less to be regarded. Nam quae de gratia Dei iustificante scholastici seribunt, commentitia universa existimo, saith Cardinal Pighius, who is therefore much condemned by Bellarmine, but without cause.\nVer.",
    "Commentary Vol. 163": "Ft81 --  R. Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]` Albo in Sepher lkkarim, 50:4. c."
  },
